Anonymous Thu 09 Dec 2021 02:33:27 No.43814624 Report

>>43814387
Scales are a form of fur. In fish, the color is in the skin, which determines the color of the scales that grow out of that particular skin location. The same for fur. If there is a way to program the color of the skin down at the genetic level, anything growing out of that skin would be the color determined by the cells that the fur/scales grow from.

Interesting variation in thought here is that the bare skin might be one color, but the fur or scales that grow out of it might be another. The color of the skin indicates the pattern, but the material that composes fur/scales might take on a different hue or shade due to how the color sets & cures in the fur ... meaning, the "living" color in healthy skin with blood flow could be different from the "dead" color (probably more concentrated) in the fur that grew out of a particular skin patch.

The "tattoo" process isn't insertion of dye into the skin, it's a treatment of some sort that forces the treated cells in the skin to create and concentrate pigments.

Which might be directly affected by diet. So, an anthro with a skin pattern treatment to express a fur pattern might have to follow a specific diet to get the colors they desire. Or take specific supplements. Lack of the correct diet/supplements might make th colors change or fade.

Anonymous Thu 09 Dec 2021 08:38:02 No.43820902 Report

>>43814894
>Let me know what you guys think.
I'd assume this is a beta release concept draft? Does a fair job of immediately laying out a setting & staging it. I've the advantage of already knowing this is mid-19th century Earth and appears to departing from England, so a huge amount of detail gets auto-filled in. That's worth a few moments to imagine as an author, because it makes some things easier for you, but also keep in mind that different readers will auto-fill certain details differently than others (and you) based upon their education for the era. Meaning, some people may be filling in data that's wrong & otherwise based upon misconceptions, including myself.

It's expecting too much to fill all that in yourself, or to fill in more essentials in such a short intro piece. Just keep that in mind as you move forward. It's going to be on you to drop some authentic period detail that's relevant so readers aren't imagining cell phones or radio equipment & such.

The "hundreds" for each ship is a bit much. Colony ships might carry 200 to 300, but high seas working class might have 20 to 50 crew plus a dozen or two passengers.

Don't know what research you've done for the era. The 40" barrel length on the gun seems it *might* be right? I've fired a bit of black powder and it seems slightly long for Civil War era, but I might be remembering it wrong. It's a nitpick detail anyway since if 36" is correct it's hardly a difference. It would not be the sort of rifle to shoot ducks with, I hope obviously. Keep in mind the weight of that gun will be significant, if it plays into any plot points you intend.

> “Taken” a feminine voice from above snarls
Not sure our MC would recognize her voice as necessarily feminine, since this may be the first time ever he's interacted with a cat. Maybe he wouldn't even recognize her as female. Don't think it would be obvious (yet) that he completely lacks tattoos, given "formal" clothing would reveal little bare skin.
